"What technology is the closest to having all these capabilities?"
There is no definitive answer to which technology is the closest to having all these capabilities, as different methods may have different advantages and disadvantages depending on the situation. However, based on my search results, I can provide some possible criteria for comparison, such as:

- **Depth range**: This is the maximum depth that the rescue system can operate at. The deeper the depth, the more challenging the rescue becomes. Based on my search results, the DSRV has the highest depth range of up to **1,500 meters**, followed by the SRDRS and the rescue capsule at **610 meters** and **250 meters** respectively¹  . The depth range of the air line and diving operations may vary depending on the equipment and conditions²⁴.
- **Capacity**: This is the number of people that the rescue system can carry or assist at a time. The higher the capacity, the faster the rescue can be completed. Based on my search results, the DSRV has the highest capacity of up to **24 people**, followed by the SRDRS at **16 people** and the rescue capsule at **9 people**¹  . The capacity of the air line and diving operations may also vary depending on the equipment and conditions²⁴.
- **Transportability**: This is the ease of transporting the rescue system to the accident site. The faster and easier the transport, the sooner the rescue can begin. Based on my search results, the SRDRS is designed to be transportable by truck, aircraft or ship, and can use a vessel of opportunity as a mother ship. The DSRV is also transportable by aircraft or ship, but requires a specially configured attack submarine as a mother ship. The rescue capsule may be deployed from a surface ship or a submarine³. The air line and diving operations may require special vessels or equipment to be transported²⁴.
- **Interoperability**: This is the ability of the rescue system to work with different types of submarines from different nations. The higher the interoperability, the more versatile and cooperative the rescue can be. Based on my search results, both the DSRV and the SRDRS have been involved in multinational exercises and agreements to enhance their interoperability with other submarine rescue systems . The NATO Submarine Rescue System (NSRS) is a joint project of Britain, France and Norway that replaced their previous systems with a similar design to the SRDRS². The rescue capsule may have limited interoperability depending on its compatibility with different submarine hatches³. The air line and diving operations may also have limited interoperability depending on their availability and suitability for different submarines²⁴.

I hope this comparison helps you understand some of the factors that may affect the choice of submarine rescue technology.

